03851nam a22006495i 9780823298303DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232983037 a10.1515/97808232983032doi  a(DE-B1597)612811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBF175.5.P54bM3713 2021 7aPSY0260002bisacsh04a150.19521 aMartínez Ruiz, Rosaura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEros :bBeyond the Death Drive /cRosaura Martínez Ruiz. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEros considers a promise left unfulfilled in Sigmund Freud’s Beyond the Pleasure Principle. Rosaura Martínez Ruiz argues that when the pleasure principle comes into contact with the death drive (the human tendency toward aggression or cruelty), the psyche can take detours that, without going beyond the limit of the pleasure principle, can nevertheless defer it. Eros reflects on these deviations of the pleasure principle, in the political sphere and in the intimate realm. Following these erotic paths, Martínez argues that the forces of the death drive can only be resisted if resistance is understood as an ongoing process. In such an effort, erotic action and the construction of pathways for sublimation are never-ending ethical and political tasks. We know that these tasks cannot be finally accomplished, yet they remain imperative and undeniably urgent.If psychoanalysis and deconstruction teach us that the death drive is insurmountable, through aesthetic creation and political action we can nevertheless delay, defer, and postpone it. Calling for the formation and maintenance of a “community of mourning duelists,” this book seeks to imagine and affirm the kind of “erotic battalion” that might yet be mobilized against injustice. This battalion’s mourning, Martínez argues, must be ongoing, open-ended, combative, and tenaciously committed to the complexity of ethical and political life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aDeath instinct. 0aPleasure principle (Psychology). 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith.1 aMcGlazer, Ramsey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823298303zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823298303423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823298303/original  a978-3-11-073909-1  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK